                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18360201-608-offence-1 t18360201-name-1327"></join>John Hunt</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1328" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1328" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1328" type="surname" value="WILSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1328" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE WILSON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police constable L</hi> 62) On the morning of the 31st of January. I went to No, 2, Salamanca-court, Lamneth, and found the prisoner—I told him I had received information from a female that he had been robbing his employer—he went up stairs—I followed him, and saw him unlock a box, and take this parcel out—he came down stairs, put it on the table, and said it was Cayonne—I asked him where he got it from—he said it was Mr. Hun's—he said, "There is the stolen property"—I took him to Mr. Hunt's and he again said it was his property—it contained 4<hi rend="italic">lbs</hi>. of Cayenne pepper—I returned to his house, and found 2<hi rend="italic">lbs</hi>. of mustard in the same box.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PAYNE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> He made no difficulty about it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> None whatever,</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18360201-name-1329" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1329" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1329" type="surname" value="HUNT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18360201-name-1329" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HUNT</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Prince's-street, Lambeth, The prisoner was two years in my employ—he was brought to my house with this property—he asked me if his wife had been there—I said she had, and she had made a charge against him of robbing me, but I said I did not belive it, and or<lb></lb>dered her cut of the yard—he said it was true, and what the policeman.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183602010228"></xptr>
               <p>has got was my property—I had very great confidence in him—he had the whole management of this department—I grind the Cayenne myself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long was he in your employ? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Two or three years—I thought him a good character—the mustard was not produced—he treated this very jocularly—I have been robbed of many times by servants without prosecuting them. that I was obliged to prosecute him—I think he did not expect that I should—he had 28<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., a-week.</p>
               <p>(Thomas Bullock, of Rochester; and William Thomas Burley, engraver, James-street, New-cut; gave the prisoner a good character.)</p>
               <p>
